### (1) Translation of the Story into English (with Chinese Proper Names)

**Original Passage (relevant excerpt):**

> 魏武侯謀事而當，群臣莫能逮，退朝而有喜色。  
> 吳起進曰：「亦嘗有以楚莊王之語，聞於左右者乎？」  
> 武侯曰：「楚莊王之語何如？」  
> 吳起對曰：「楚莊王謀事而當，群臣莫能逮，退朝而有憂色。申公巫臣進問曰：『王朝而有憂色，何也？』莊王曰：『不穀謀事而當，群臣莫能逮，是以憂也。其在中蘬之言也，曰：『諸侯自為得師者王，得友者霸，得疑者存，自為謀而莫己若者亡。』今以不穀之不肖，而群臣莫能逮，國幾於亡乎！』」  
> 楚莊王以憂，而君以喜。  
> 武侯逡巡再拜曰：「天使夫子振寡人之過也。」

**English Translation:**

> Emperor Wu of Wei was plotting a coup when the time was right, but the ministers could not catch him in the act. After he abdicated and took his leave, he appeared to be happy. Wu Zhi (the official) approached and said, "Have you ever heard the words of King Cheng of Chu spoken to someone?"  
> Wu of Wei replied, "What were the words of King Cheng of Chu?"  
> Wu Zhi explained: "King Cheng of Chu was plotting a coup at the right moment, but the ministers could not apprehend him. After he abdicated, he was troubled in spirit. A minister named Feng Zhi asked him why he was troubled. The king said, 'I did not scheme while in power; the ministers could not catch me. That is why I am troubled. It is the saying within the secret records: "The kings who seek to become rulers by forming their own alliances are strong in friends, cautious with doubts, but if they plot while lacking self-awareness, their state will perish." Now, because I did not scheme with wisdom and the ministers could not catch me, our country is nearly lost! That is why I am troubled.' King Cheng of Chu was troubled, but the emperor was happy."  
> Wu of Wei, upon revisiting the matter, kowtowed and said, "May Heaven reward the sage Xunzi for correcting the faults of the people."

